In Java, the == operator is used to compare whether two objects refer to the same object, while the .equals() method is used to compare the values of the objects. The == operator is a relation operator, while the .equals() method is a logical equivalence (or comparison) operator.

Here's a brief summary of when to use each:

1. == operator (reference equality):

Use the == operator when you want to compare if two objects refer to the same object in memory. This is particularly useful when working with objects and reference types, such as classes or interfaces.

Examples:
```java
class Person {
    String name;
    int age;

    public Person(String name, int age) {
        this.name = name;
        this.age = age;
    }

    public boolean equals(Object obj) {
        if (this == obj) {
            return true;
        }
        if (obj == null) {
            return false;
        }
        if (getClass() != obj.getClass()) {
            return false;
        }
        Person other = (Person) obj;
        return this.name.equals(other.name) && this.age == other.age;
    }
}
```
In this example, the `Person` class overrides the `equals` method to compare objects by their `name` and `age` properties using the `.equals()` method.
```java
// Correct
if (new Person("John", 30) == new Person("John", 30)) {
    System.out.println("They are equal");
}

// Incorrect
if ("John" == new Person("John", 30).name) {
    System.out.println("They have the same name");
}
```
1. .equals() method (value equality):

Use the .equals() method when you want to compare the values of the objects. This is particularly useful when working with primitive types or objects that implement the `Object.equals()` method.

Examples:
```java
class Point {
    int x, y;

    public Point(int x, int y) {
        this.x = x;
        this.y = y;
    }

    public boolean equals(Object obj) {
        if (this == obj) {
            return true;
        }
        if (obj == null) {
            return false;
        }
        if (getClass() != obj.getClass()) {
            return false;
        }
        Point other = (Point) obj;
        return this.x == other.x && this.y == other.y;
    }
}
```
In this example, the `Point` class overrides the `equals` method to compare objects by their `x` and `y` properties using the `.equals()` method.
```java
// Correct
if (new Point(3, 4) == new Point(3, 4)) {
    System.out.println("They are equal");
}

// Incorrect
if (3 == new Point(3, 4).x) {
    System.out.println("They have the same x-coordinate");
}
```
When to use == operator:

* When comparing references (objects)
* When overriding the `Object.equals()` method

When to use .equals() method:

* When comparing the values of primitive types or objects that implement `Object.equals()`

In summary, use the == operator when comparing references and use the `.equals()` method when comparing values. Remember that strings in Java are immutable, and the `==` operator compares references while the `.equals()` method compares the values of the strings. Using the `.equals()` method is usually safer and more appropriate for comparing strings in Java.

Here's a solution using bitwise operations and logic to determine if a number is a power of three:
```java
import java.util.BitSet;

public class ThreePower {
    public static boolean isThreePower(int n) {
        // Base case: n is less than 0 and negative
        if (n < 0) return false;

        // Break early if the number is not a power of three
        if (n < 3) return false;

        // Convert n to binary and create a bitset for the power of three
        BitSet powerThree = new BitSet(32);
        powerThree.set(0);
        powerThree.set(1);
        powerThree.set(2);

        // Bitwise and the binary representation of n with the power of three
        int mask = powerThree.cardinality();
        return (n & mask) == mask;
    }
}
```
This solution uses the `BitSet` class to represent the power of three (110) in binary and applies bitwise operations to check if the input number has the same binary representation. The `cardinality()` method of the `BitSet` class returns the number of set bits in the set, which is equal to the power of three in this case.

